<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="649" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="30.[133,1343,2092,3267]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[134,377,2877,2910]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
The 
<collectingCountry box="[463,607,2877,2910]" name="Seychelles" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">Seychelles</collectingCountry>
Free-tailed Bat is nocturnal. Roosts are mostly associated with public buildings in the French colonial style, as these have enclosed attics.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="649" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="30.[133,1343,2092,3267]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,862,2995,3028]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[879,1020,2995,3028]" name="Seychelles" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">Seychelles</collectingCountry>
Free-tailed Bats roost communally in small colonies. Both maternity and mixed-sex colonies have been observed. Based on interviews with people occupying buildings with roosts, colonies may migrate during the cold season.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
